driver tried to look at *pos anyway", and<br />&gt; that will give you a nice OOPS instead.<br /><br />Confirmed. At least the x86 firmware update code uses<br />"simple_read_from_buffer()", which does use the file position, but<br />doesn't actually allow llseek().<br /><br />So no, "it's a character device no llseek" does not mean that it acts<br />as a pure streaming device with no file position, and we'd actually<br />have to mark individual drivers (either by adding 'stream_open()' in<br />their open routines, or adding the extra field to 'struct<br />file_operations' that I mentioned).<br /><br />I think I'll have to revert that trial commit. I'll give it another<br />day in case somebody has a better idea, but it looks like it's too<br />early to do that nice cleanup as things are now.<br /><br />              Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
